            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-ling Chen lives and breathes art, quite literally. Her apartment sits directly above Chen Contemporary, the Hayes Valley gallery she founded fifteen years ago. Her 0.0-mile commute is a testament to a life where personal and professional passions have completely merged.\n\nBorn and raised in San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District, Mei-ling is the only child of pragmatic Chinese immigrants who ran a successful laundromat. They preached the virtues of stability, hoping she\u2019d pursue medicine or law. But Mei-ling was captivated by a different legacy: the hushed stories of her grandfather, a master ceramicist in Guangzhou whose art was lost to the Cultural Revolution. This ancestral ghost fueled a quiet rebellion within her.\n\nShe attended UC Berkeley, pleasing her parents initially, but majored in Art History. The true break came when she moved to New York for her Master\u2019s degree, focusing on East Asian contemporary art. After graduation, she spent a decade working as a junior curator in Chelsea, learning the ruthless but exhilarating business of art. Though successful, she felt disconnected, a facilitator for stories that weren't hers to tell.\n\nThe turning point was her mother's passing. The small inheritance, combined with her own disciplined savings, was just enough. At 39, she took the monumental risk of returning to San Francisco and leasing a ground-floor space in a still-developing Hayes Valley. She opened Chen Contemporary with a singular mission: to provide a platform for emerging Asian diaspora artists whose voices, like her grandfather's, might otherwise be silenced.\n\nNow 54 and amicably divorced from a man who never fully understood her devotion to the gallery, Mei-ling\u2019s life is one of curated purpose. Her days begin with tea overlooking the neighborhood, followed by afternoons negotiating with collectors and mentoring young artists. Her social life is a calendar of openings and artist dinners. Though close with her tech-investor son, the gallery remains her truest partner. Her dream is no longer just to run a successful business, but to establish an endowment, ensuring that Chen Contemporary becomes a permanent anchor for future generations of artists in the ever-changing cultural landscape of her beloved city."
